title: KafkaSource sets actual high watermark in workunits
body:
ETL-3352. High watermark was originally set into `WorkUnitState` by `KafkaExtractor`. However, if `KafkaExtractor` fails before the high watermark is set, and its `WorkUnitState` is still committed (which may happen if job.commit.policy is set to partial), the next run may lose checkpoint.

Now `KafkaSource` sets actual high watermark into `WorkUnit`s.

Also, not sure why `State` has both `getProp` and `getProperty`. Deprecated `getProperty`.

We annotate metrics and tracking events with a cluster identifier ("clusterIdentifier"). Currently, we use the Hadoop RM or JT URL. We've got some feedback from the DWH team to have a more human- readable ID.

I've added a new class ClustersNames. It will look for a standard resource GobblinClustersNames.properties which contains a properties collection (map) from a resource manager/job tracker url to a human-readable string. If the resource is missing and/or there isn't an entry for a given URL, a normalized URL form will be used.

title: Persist state and commit data on a per-dataset basis
body:
1. A `WorkUnit` can be specified to belong to a dataset group by using a new config property `dataset.urn`.
2. Job/task state will be persisted on a per-dataset basis into different state store files, one per dataset. All `current` dataset state store files will be loaded in the next job run. 
3. Commit of data will be done on a per-dataset basis, allowing datasets to be committed independently.
4. For existing job that does not have a dataset concept or only deals with a single dataset, the logic of job/task state persistence and data commit remains the same.

Signed-off-by: Yinan Li liyinan926@gmail.com

title: Separate SourceState/JobState from workUnits
body:
Summary:
- Deprecated all constructors of `WorkUnit`, and added some factory methods, which do not add job states to workunits. 
  The reason to use factory methods is to avoid having too many constructors for `WorkUnit`, some deprecated and some not deprecated.
- Deprecated the constructor of `Extract` that takes `SourceState`, added a new constructor without `SourceState`.
- In `MRJobLauncher.prepareHadoopJob()`, serialize `jobState` into a file. Then in `TaskRunner.setup()`, read `jobState` from the file and add it to each `workUnit`.
- In `LocalJobLauncher.runWorkUnits()`, add `jobState` to each `workUnit`.
- In `MRJobLauncher.runWorkUnits()`, combine `jobState` with each `workUnit` into a `fatWorkUnit`, since properties from both `jobState` and `workUnit` are needed in order to invoke `JobLauncherUtils.cleanStagingData()`.
- Modified `KafkaSource` to use the new paradigm.

Tested with Kafka adapter. Existing source implementations still work.

title: Fixing bugs in MultiWorkUnit
body:
Since the `MultiWorkUnit` class extends `WorkUnit` it is possible for a user to execute the following code:

```
WorkUnit workUnit = new MultiWorkUnit(Lists.newArrayList(new WorkUnit(), new WorkUnit());
workUnit.setProp("key1", "value1");
```

In the current implementation of `MultiWorkUnit` the `setProp("key1", "value1")` method will add the k, v pair to the internal properties object of the `MultiWorkUnit`, but it won't add the property to the `WorkUnit`s in the internal list.

The current implementation / usage has a few issues:

1: The k, v pair gets dropped when a `MultiWorkUnit` gets serialized.
2: The `JobLauncherUtils.flattenWorkUnits` method will also drop all these properties.

The approach I took to remedy this is to override the `setProp` method to invoke `super.setProp()` and to invoke `setProp()` on each individual `WorkUnit` in the internal list. Also, to fix the serialization bug.

I find it a little confusing that now a `MultiWorkUnit` can hold state in addition to a list of `WorkUnit`s so I am open to suggestions for a better approach.

I consider (and briefly talked to Yinan about this today), just overriding `setProp` and `getProp` with implementations that throw `UnsupportedOperationException`, but realized that would require overriding at least 5 methods. It would also be against Object Oriented Design, as `MultiWorkUnit` extends `State` and thus should be capable of storing and retrieving k, v pairs.

@liyinan926 and @ibuenros any comments or suggestions?

title: several fixes and optimizations for compaction
body:
1. Added code to add dependency jars to distributed cache.
2. In Mapper class, created method `populateRecord` to replace `AvroUtils.convertRecordSchema`, which is more efficient, since `AvroUtils.convertRecordSchema` needs to serialize the record to byte array and then deserialize it.
3. For Avro key schema, created method `removeUncomparableFields` to replace `getAllFieldsExceptMap`, since we not only need to remove MAP fields, but also need to remove ARRAY and ENUM fields, as well as UNIONS that contain one of those types. Also, `getAllFieldsExceptMap` was not recursive, which is now fixed.

The reason to remove those fields in Avro key schema is that a schema that contains these fields cannot be used as the dedup key.

title: Fixed a bug that may cause a job to hang if its tasks fail to getExtractor
body:
This bug is affecting stand-alone jobs using `LocalJobLauncher` that may hang if any of its tasks fails to `getExtractor`. In this case, the `finally` part of the `Task.run` method will be executed, and `this.taskStateTracker.onTaskCompletion(this)` is called. In the implementation class `LocalTaskStateTracker2`, `this.taskExecutor.retry(task)` is called, which will throw an exception on `task.getTaskState().getPropAsInt(ConfigurationKeys.FORK_BRANCHES_KEY)` since the key `FORK_BRANCHES_KEY` is not set because the task failed before the number of branches is known and that key is set. This runtime exception is thrown in the `finally` clause and is not caught, causing the task to hang.
